ody":"Susannah Smith married Rev. Benjamin Tallmadge of Setauket. Their son Benjamin grew up to run the Culper spy ring for General Washington during the Revolution."}],"slug":"susannah-tallmadge-1729"},"I00140":{"id":"I00140","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1702,"month":5,"day":5,"city":"Newport Pagnell","county":"Buckinghamshire","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1771,"month":2,"day":26,"city":"White Plains","state":"New York"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM579","plot_notes":"First Presbyterian Church Cemetery, White Plains NY; later church construction extended over his grave. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"parents":{"mother_research_notes":"Susannah Odell","father_research_notes":"Thomas Smith of Rye, NY"},"church_roles":[{"role":"Pastor","location":"Rye, New York","dates":"ordained Dec 13, 1742"},{"role":"Pastor","location":"White Plains, New York","dates":"later years"},{"role":"Occasional preacher","location":"Sing Sing, New York","dates":"1763-1768"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00109","children_ids":["H00320","H00321","H00322","H00323","H00324","H00325","H00326","H00327","H00328","H00329","H00330","H00331"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 109"},{"short":"Smith-Hooker Genealogy by Della Bishop, 1936"},{"short":"Yale Biographical Sketches 1701-1745 (1885)","page":"359"}],"gender":"male","tags":["yale_graduate","physician","minister"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["physician","minister"],"notable_blurb":"Physician-minister at White Plains for thirty years","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/62188479/john-smith","primary_url_label":"FindAGrave"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"X00128","display_label":"Young friend in New York who drew him toward the ministry","link_text":"Jonathan Edwards"}],"education":[{"school_name":"Yale College","graduation_year":1727,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"title":"Rev. Dr.","display_name":"Rev. Dr. John Smith","first_name":"John","last_name":"Smith","married_names":[],"gender":"male"},"residence":{"city":"White Plains","county":"Westchester","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1727"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"career":[{"role":"Physician","organization":"Rye and White Plains, NY","end_year":1771,"notes":"Practiced medicine alongside ministry for nearly 30 years. 'Said to have been a very successful physician... remarkably successful in cases of insanity.'"},{"role":"Presbyterian Minister","organization":"White Plains Presbyterian Church","end_year":1771,"notes":"Served the White Plains church which was destroyed in the Battle of White Plains October 1776, seven years after his death."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"relationships","header":"Walked the Hudson with Jonathan Edwards as friend","body":"He was a personal friend of Jonathan Edwards, the most important American theologian of the eighteenth century. On one occasion, walking together along the banks of the Hudson, Smith confided to Edwards: 'To be separated from my endeared friends and companions are the most bitter trials of my life.' The friendship spanned Smith's quarter-century at White Plains and Edwards's career through Northampton, Stockbridge, and Princeton."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Physician and Presbyterian minister for thirty years","body":"He practiced medicine and ministry simultaneously at Rye and White Plains for nearly thirty years — a rare dual vocation in colonial America. Contemporaries described him as 'remarkably successful in cases of insanity.' His Yale class of 1727 trained him for ministry; the medicine he taught himself."},{"number":3,"category":"historical","header":"His church destroyed at Battle of White Plains","body":"Seven years after his death in 1771, the Battle of White Plains was fought in front of his Presbyterian church on Oct 28, 1776 — and the building was destroyed. A second church on the same ground was later destroyed by fire. The third — built of gray stone — was eventually extended over his grave, and the original upright slab was moved further back."},{"number":4,"category":"clergy","header":"A church was later built over his grave","body":"Rev. Dr. John Smith served nearly thirty years as Presbyterian minister at Rye and White Plains. After his death the White Plains meetinghouse was rebuilt over his burial spot, and his gravestone was moved back to accommodate it."}],"slug":"john-smith-1702"},"H00109":{"id":"H00109","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1704,"month":5,"day":10,"city":"Guilford","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00031","mother_id":"I00061"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 109"},{"short":"Smith-Hooker Genealogy by Della Bishop, 1936, Ithaca NY"}],"death":{"year":1775,"month":9,"day":5,"city":"White Plains","state":"New York"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00140","children_ids":["H00320","H00321","H00322","H00323","H00324","H00325","H00326","H00327","H00328","H00329","H00330","H00331"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1724,"date_month":5,"date_day":6,"location_city":"Guilford","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00757","display_label":"Mehitable Hooker Smith is the great-grandmother of Maj. Benjamin Tallmadge.","link_text":"Maj. Benjamin Tallmadge Jr."}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Mehitable Hooker Smith","notes":"Also called \"Mabel\" per EH","first_name":"Mehitable","last_name":"Smith","married_names":["Smith"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Twelve children with Rev. John Smith of Rye","body":"She married Rev. John Smith of Rye, New York, and had twelve children between 1727 and 1750. The family lived in Westchester County during the years just before the Revolution turned that border country into a no-man's land."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Great-grandmother of Washington's spymaster","body":"Her great-grandson Major Benjamin Tallmadge ran the Culper Ring for George Washington — the network that exposed Benedict Arnold's 1780 treason. Tallmadge was a classmate of Nathan Hale and a fellow Hooker descendant."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Daughter Abigail at Washington's White Plains headquarters","body":"Her daughter Abigail Smith married Jacob Purdy, whose Purchase, NY house served as Washington's headquarters during the Battle of White Plains in 1776 and again in 1778. The Purdy descendants would carry the line through several Patriot–Loyalist conflicts."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"She and her sister married two Smith brothers","body":"Mehitable Hooker married Rev. Dr. John Smith of Rye. Her elder sister Hannah had married his brother Thomas, so two Hooker sisters wed two Smith brothers."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM579","plot_notes":"First Presbyterian Church Cemetery, White Plains NY. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"slug":"mehitable-smith-1704"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}